metadata.name: olho do furacão #16
metadata.description:
No centro o movimento é imperceptível, mas quando olhamos para o extremo ele se move tão rápido quanto nossa percepção pode suportar, o ruído gira e na fusão das abóbadas essa confluência de modulações nos coloca no centro do furacão.

In the center the movement is imperceptible but when we look at the extreme it moves as fast as our perception can carry, the noise swirls and in the merging of the vaults this confluence of modulations places us in the center of the hurricane. 

960x960 for gpus, you can press 'a' to change the resolution to minimal 256x256 recomended to tiny systems, web video synthesizer patchwork made on hydra.ojack.xyz

Fxhash
Wednesday, April 30, 2025

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #260
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Luminocity #42
metadata.description:
Millions of lights shine forth from the windows of the city. Who lives behind those windows? What do they see when they look out?

The light shining down from distant stars. Do those stars have planets and cities with lights of their own?

--------------------------

This is a 100% code generated project. Outputs are created in either night, sunrise, or sunset mode and at a default resolution of 1500 x 1000.

Click on the output and use these keys to change it:
'n' - change to night
'u' - change to sunrise
'd' - change to sunset
's' - save at current resolution
'2' - change to  3000 x 2000 resolution
'3' - change to  4500 x 3000 resolution
...
'8' - change to 12000 x 8000 resolution

URL Parameters: You can also set the time and resolution in the url.
To change the time mode append on the end of the url &time=sunset  (or night/sunrise)
To change the resolution append &res=2 (or 3-8)

Copyright 2023 Jeff Clark
--------------------------
100% generative

All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using standard javascript and canvas 2D api

metadata.name: Ersbla #600
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: Skravert #241
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Florescence #309
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.
